		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="head">
					<marginalia_text>
						Nescia virtus stare loco. Et Ars mora[e] impatiens,
						solis vacat necessarijs momenti punctis: /
					</marginalia_text>
					<X-ref book_title="Pharsalia" language="LA" person="Lucan" text="Nescia virtus stare loco"/>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						eademq[ue] expedit rotundissimè.
						Vtriusq[ue] dua[e] Singulares laudes:
						Celeritas, et Perfectio. 
						Ante singulos: et super omnes.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				'His virtue not knowing how to stand in one place.' 
				And Art, impatient of delay, is free to consider the necessary points of the situation alone;
				And at the same time, it obtains its goal most smoothly.
				The singular praise of both quickness and perfection.
				Before other singular matters, and above all things.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
					<marginalia_text>
						Profundè Pragmaticus veterator: Facit gratum
						fortuna, quam nemo videt.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				The pragmatic man is profoundly experienced:
				luck, which no one sees, makes one grateful.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="270" place="right_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Eutrapelus nusq[uam] ha[e]ret: sed, dicit, scribit, negociatur, quiduis facit omniu[m] celerrimè,
						singulorumq[ue] absolutissimè. Industria si non maior, at efficacior.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Eutrapelus"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Eutrapelus never clings to things, but he says, writes, and performs whatever he can do, more quickly than all other men,
				and more completely than all other singular men. His industriousness, if it isn't better, it is more efficient.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
